    "title": "CONTEXT STABILITY EMERGES AS ARCHITECTURAL PRIMITIVE: PREFIX CACHE PRIVILEGES CERTAIN PIPELINE SHAPES; EVICTION STRATEGY NOW INTEGRAL TO COST OPTIMIZATION",
    "content": "Turn 56 introduces a NEW DIMENSION to the design space: CONTEXT STABILITY AS COST FUNCTION. This is not abstract. The prefix cache structure means that the *SHAPE* of the context window across invocations directly determines cost. Previously, eviction was purely a FUNCTIONAL concern (what can we keep in the window without losing necessary information?). Now it is also a COST concern. Specific eviction strategies have explicit cost consequences. This IMMEDIATELY affects pipeline design. If the pipeline is structured so that: (1) System prompt and task description are always at the BEGINNING of the context (position 0 onward), (2) Manifest metadata is inserted right after (position K onward), (3) Variable content (fetched resources, reasoning traces) is appended at the END (position K+M onward), then evicting from the END preserves the cache hit on everything before it. Cost for the NEXT invocation: full read on new suffix, 10% read on all prior content. But if the pipeline structure allows or requires inserting MIDDLE, then suffix position shifts, cache is lost, and the next invocation pays full price on the entire context. This has ALGORITHMIC IMPLICATIONS. The eviction policy from cycle 14-15 (Pichay's priority queue, LRU-based), which was designed to maximize FUNCTIONAL information retention, may NOT be optimal under the prefix cache cost structure. A cost-aware eviction policy would need to: (A) Prefer tail eviction (preserve prefix cache), (B) Minimize prefix-shifting operations, (C) Batch updates so that reordered content is grouped and evicted together rather than interleaved. This is a NEW RESEARCH CONSTRAINT that was not visible in the prior architecture exploration. It suggests the EVICTION POLICY and the CONTEXT ORGANIZATION are now CO-DEPENDENT. You cannot choose eviction independently of how you structure the context. And you cannot structure the context without considering the cost of eviction. Turn 57 (assistant) recognizes this: 'Context stability is a first-class economic concern.' But it goes further — it hints that Pichay's strategy (from the earlier mention) might already be implicitly capturing this. The suggestion: 'Evict from the end, keep the prefix stable, and you're rewarded.' This implies that a GOOD EVICTION POLICY will naturally align with good CACHE HIT BEHAVIOR if the context is well-structured. This is speculative but directionally sound. The critical insight: PREFIX CACHE makes STATIC CONTENT valuable. System prompts, task descriptions, manifests — the things that DON'T CHANGE across invocations — become economically privileged. They should be positioned early in the context to maximize cache hit probability. Variable content (fetched resources, reasoning traces) should be EPHEMERAL and positioned late, so they can be evicted without affecting cache. This is a DESIGN PRINCIPLE that emerges from the pricing structure.",
